<subsection xml:id="subsec-vectors">
    <title>Brief reminder: vectors</title>

    <introduction>
        <p>
            In physics, many real-world quantities—such as force, velocity, or displacement—cannot be fully described by a single number. For example, if you apply a force to push a box, the outcome depends not only on how hard you push (the magnitude) but also on the direction in which you are pushing.
        </p>
        <p>
            To capture both magnitude and direction simultaneously, we use mathematical objects called vectors. This concept extends naturally beyond physical space into abstract mathematics, allowing us to handle multi-dimensional spaces and systems.
        </p>
    </introduction>

    <definition xml:id="def-vector">
        <title>Vector</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A <term>vector</term> of size <m>n</m> is an ordered tuple of <m>n</m> real numbers. The set of all vectors of size <m>n</m> is denoted by <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>. A vector <m>\mathbf{v} \in \mathbb{R}^n</m> is commonly written as
                <m>\mathbf{v} = (v_1, \dots, v_n)</m>
                or in column form as
                <me>\mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} v_1 \\ \vdots \\ v_n \end{pmatrix}.</me>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
        Let us look at a concrete numerical representation of a vector in three-dimensional space.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="ex-vector">
        <title>A Vector in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m></title>
        <p>
            An example of a vector in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m> is
            <me>\mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ -1 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix}.</me>
        </p>
    </example>

    <p>
        In <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> and <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>, vectors can be visualized as arrows in Euclidean space. In this geometric interpretation, a vector has a direction and a length, but it is not tied to a fixed starting point. A particularly useful representative is the position vector that starts at the origin.
    </p>

    <p>
        At the same time, the algebraic point of view is more general: a vector is determined by its components. The geometric picture is very helpful in two and three dimensions, but the coordinate description remains meaningful in arbitrary dimension.
    </p>

    <p>
        To make vectors useful, we need mathematical rules for how to combine them. The two most fundamental operations are adding two vectors and multiplying a vector by a real number.
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-vector-operations">
        <title>Vector Operations</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>\mathbf{v}, \mathbf{w} \in \mathbb{R}^n</m> and let <m>\lambda \in \mathbb{R}</m>. The sum of two vectors of the same size and the scalar multiple of a vector are defined component-wise.
            </p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Addition</title>
                    <p>
                        The sum of <m>\mathbf{v}</m> and <m>\mathbf{w}</m> is
                        <me>\mathbf{v}+\mathbf{w} = \begin{pmatrix} v_1+w_1 \\ \vdots \\ v_n+w_n \end{pmatrix}.</me>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Scalar Multiplication</title>
                    <p>
                        The scalar multiple of <m>\mathbf{v}</m> by <m>\lambda</m> is
                        <me>\lambda \mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} \lambda v_1 \\ \vdots \\ \lambda v_n \end{pmatrix}.</me>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </statement>
    </definition>

    <example xml:id="ex-vector-operations">
        <title>Calculating Sums and Scalar Multiples</title>
        <p>
            Let
            <m>\mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix}</m>
            and
            <m>\mathbf{w} = \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ -2 \end{pmatrix}</m>
            be vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            Their sum is
            <me>\mathbf{v} + \mathbf{w} = \begin{pmatrix} 1+4 \\ 3+(-2) \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 5 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}.</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            If we scale <m>\mathbf{v}</m> by <m>\lambda = 3</m>, we obtain
            <me>3\mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} 3 \cdot 1 \\ 3 \cdot 3 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ 9 \end{pmatrix}.</me>
        </p>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-engineering-resultant-force">
        <title>Resultant Force on a Mechanical Component</title>
        <p>
            Suppose two forces act on a component in the plane:
            <me>\mathbf{F}_1 = \begin{pmatrix} 120 \\ 40 \end{pmatrix}\text{ N}, \qquad \mathbf{F}_2 = \begin{pmatrix} -30 \\ 90 \end{pmatrix}\text{ N}.</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            The total force is obtained by vector addition:
            <me>\mathbf{F}_{\text{res}} = \mathbf{F}_1 + \mathbf{F}_2 = \begin{pmatrix} 120 + (-30) \\ 40 + 90 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 90 \\ 130 \end{pmatrix}\text{ N}.</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            Thus, the component experiences a resultant force with horizontal component <m>90\text{ N}</m> and vertical component <m>130\text{ N}</m>.
        </p>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-engineering-force-scaling">
        <title>Scaling a Force Vector</title>
        <p>
            Suppose a force acting on a component is represented by
            <me>\mathbf{F} = \begin{pmatrix} 120 \\ 40 \end{pmatrix}\text{ N}.</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            If the same force is applied with twice the intensity, the new force vector is
            <me>2\mathbf{F} = \begin{pmatrix} 240 \\ 80 \end{pmatrix}\text{ N}.</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            This illustrates scalar multiplication: all components are multiplied by the same scalar, so the direction remains the same while the magnitude changes.
        </p>
    </example>  

    <figure xml:id="fig-geogebra-vector-addition">
        <title>Interactive: Vector Addition</title>
        <interactive geogebra="vgqcxgyn" aspect="4:3" width="100%">
            <instructions>
                <p>Drag the heads of vectors <m>\mathbf{v}</m> and <m>\mathbf{w}</m> to see how their sum <m>\mathbf{v}+\mathbf{w}</m> changes geometrically via the parallelogram rule.</p>
            </instructions>
        </interactive>
    </figure>

    <figure xml:id="fig-geogebra-scalar-multiplication">
        <title>Interactive: Scalar Multiplication</title>
        <interactive geogebra="jjw6ww6q" aspect="16:9" width="100%">
            <instructions>
                <p>Use the slider for <m>\lambda</m> to see how the scalar stretches, shrinks, or reverses the direction of the vector <m>\mathbf{v}</m>.</p>
            </instructions>
        </interactive>
    </figure>

    <p>
        Having established these basic arithmetic operations, a special vector arises naturally when we scale any vector by zero or subtract a vector from itself.
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-zero-vector">
        <title>Zero Vector</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The <term>zero vector</term> in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> is the vector whose components are all equal to zero. It is denoted by <m>\mathbf{0}</m> and has the form
                <me>\mathbf{0} = \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ \vdots \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}.</me>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
        Just like ordinary numbers, vector operations satisfy several basic algebraic laws.
    </p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-vector-arithmetic">
        <title>Laws of Vector Arithmetic</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                For all vectors <m>\mathbf{u}, \mathbf{v}, \mathbf{w} \in \mathbb{R}^n</m> and all scalars <m>\lambda, \mu \in \mathbb{R}</m>, the following rules hold.
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li><p><term>Associativity of Addition:</term> <m>\mathbf{u}+(\mathbf{v}+\mathbf{w})=(\mathbf{u}+\mathbf{v})+\mathbf{w}</m></p></li>
                <li><p><term>Commutativity of Addition:</term> <m>\mathbf{u}+\mathbf{v}=\mathbf{v}+\mathbf{u}</m></p></li>
                <li><p><term>Neutral Element:</term> <m>\mathbf{u}+\mathbf{0}=\mathbf{0}+\mathbf{u}=\mathbf{u}</m></p></li>
                <li><p><term>Inverse Element:</term> <m>\mathbf{u}+(-\mathbf{u})=(-\mathbf{u})+\mathbf{u}=\mathbf{0}</m></p></li>
                <li><p><term>Left Distributivity:</term> <m>\lambda(\mathbf{u}+\mathbf{v})=\lambda\mathbf{u}+\lambda\mathbf{v}</m></p></li>
                <li><p><term>Right Distributivity:</term> <m>(\lambda+\mu)\mathbf{u}=\lambda\mathbf{u}+\mu\mathbf{u}</m></p></li>
                <li><p><term>Associativity of Scalar Multiplication:</term> <m>(\lambda\mu)\mathbf{u}=\lambda(\mu\mathbf{u})</m></p></li>
                <li><p><term>Multiplication by One:</term> <m>1\mathbf{u}=\mathbf{u}</m></p></li>
            </ul>
        </statement>
    </theorem>

    <p>
        When working with several vectors, we often want to build new vectors from those already given. The most natural way to do this is to scale the vectors and then add them. In this way, we can describe how a vector can be assembled from a collection of basic directions.
    </p>

    <p>
        This idea is fundamental in linear algebra. It helps us answer questions such as: Can a given vector be generated from other vectors? Do several vectors together describe all directions in a space? And does one of the vectors contribute genuinely new information, or can it already be obtained from the others?
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-linear-combination">
        <title>Linear Combination</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>\mathbf{v}_1, \dots, \mathbf{v}_r \in \mathbb{R}^n</m> and let <m>x_1, \dots, x_r \in \mathbb{R}</m>. A vector of the form
                <me>x_1 \mathbf{v}_1 + \dots + x_r \mathbf{v}_r</me>
                is called a <term>linear combination</term> of the vectors <m>\mathbf{v}_1, \dots, \mathbf{v}_r</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>

    <example xml:id="ex-linear-combination">
        <title>A Linear Combination in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m></title>
        <p>
            Consider the vectors
            <me>\mathbf{v}_1 = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix}, \qquad \mathbf{v}_2 = \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix}.</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            Then
            <me>2\mathbf{v}_1 - \mathbf{v}_2 = 2\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix} - \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix} - \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} -1 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix}</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            Hence,
            <m>\begin{pmatrix} -1 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix}</m>
            is a linear combination of
            <m>\mathbf{v}_1</m>
            and
            <m>\mathbf{v}_2</m>.
        </p>
    </example>

    <p>
        Linear combinations tell us how new vectors can be generated from a given collection of vectors. This naturally leads to the question of whether all vectors in the collection are really needed.
    </p>

    <p>
        Indeed, it may happen that one of the vectors can already be written as a linear combination of the others. In that case, it does not contribute a genuinely new direction. To distinguish between such redundant situations and genuinely different directions, we introduce the concept of linear independence.
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-linear-independence-basis">
        <title>Linear Independence and Basis</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Vectors <m>\mathbf{v}_1, \dots, \mathbf{v}_r \in \mathbb{R}^n</m> are called <term>linearly independent</term> if the equation
                <me>x_1 \mathbf{v}_1 + \dots + x_r \mathbf{v}_r = \mathbf{0}</me>
                has only the trivial solution
                <m>x_1 = \dots = x_r = 0</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                A basis of <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> is a tuple of <m>n</m> linearly independent vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>. In that case, every vector in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> can be written uniquely as a linear combination of the basis vectors.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>

    <figure xml:id="fig-linear_dependence">
        <title>Linear dependence and linear independence</title>
        <caption>
            This graphic visualizes the concept of linear dependence and linear independence.
        </caption>
        <image xml:id="img-linear_dependence" width="100%">
            <latex-image>
                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.1, line cap=round, line join=round]

                    \tikzset{
                        axis/.style={->, thin, black},
                        vec/.style={->, very thick, black},
                        bluevec/.style={->, very thick, cyan!70!blue},
                        point/.style={circle, fill=black, inner sep=1.6pt},
                        bluepoint/.style={circle, fill=cyan!70!blue, inner sep=1.6pt},
                        plane/.style={fill=blue!20, draw=blue!50},
                        dashedhelp/.style={dashed, gray}
                    }

                    \begin{scope}[xshift=0cm]
                        \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
                        \coordinate (X) at (-2.2,-1.2);
                        \coordinate (Y) at (2.6,-0.9);
                        \coordinate (Z) at (0,2.0);

                        \coordinate (P1) at ($(O)+(X)$);
                        \coordinate (P2) at ($(O)+(Y)$);
                        \coordinate (P3) at ($(P2)+(X)$);

                        \filldraw[plane] (O) -- (P2) -- (P3) -- (P1) -- cycle;

                        \draw[axis] (O) -- (X) node[below left] {$x_1$};
                        \draw[axis] (O) -- (Y) node[right] {$x_2$};
                        \draw[axis] (O) -- (Z) node[above] {$x_3$};

                        \coordinate (U) at (-0.45,-0.82);
                        \coordinate (V) at (1.55,-0.52);
                        \coordinate (W) at (0.65,-0.95);

                        \draw[vec] (O) -- (U);
                        \draw[vec] (O) -- (V);
                        \draw[bluevec] (O) -- (W);

                        \node[point, label={[xshift=-2pt,yshift=-2pt]left:$\mathbf{u}$}] at (U) {};
                        \node[point, label={[xshift=2pt,yshift=-2pt]right:$\mathbf{v}$}] at (V) {};
                        \node[bluepoint, label={[xshift=2pt,yshift=-2pt]right:$\mathbf{w}$}] at (W) {};

                        \node[align=center] at (0,-3.2) {Linearly dependent,\\ $\mathbf{w}$ lies in the plane determined by $\mathbf{u}$ and $\mathbf{v}$};
                    \end{scope}

                    \begin{scope}[xshift=7.2cm]
                        \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
                        \coordinate (X) at (-2.2,-1.2);
                        \coordinate (Y) at (2.6,-0.9);
                        \coordinate (Z) at (0,2.0);

                        \coordinate (P1) at ($(O)+(X)$);
                        \coordinate (P2) at ($(O)+(Y)$);
                        \coordinate (P3) at ($(P2)+(X)$);

                        \filldraw[plane] (O) -- (P2) -- (P3) -- (P1) -- cycle;

                        \draw[axis] (O) -- (X) node[below left] {$x_1$};
                        \draw[axis] (O) -- (Y) node[right] {$x_2$};
                        \draw[axis] (O) -- (Z) node[above] {$x_3$};

                        \coordinate (U) at (-0.45,-0.82);
                        \coordinate (V) at (1.55,-0.52);
                        \coordinate (Wb) at (0.75,1.15);
                        \coordinate (Wp) at (0.75,-0.45);

                        \draw[vec] (O) -- (U);
                        \draw[vec] (O) -- (V);
                        \draw[bluevec] (O) -- (Wb);
                        \draw[dashedhelp] (Wp) -- (Wb);

                        \node[point, label={[xshift=-2pt,yshift=-2pt]left:$\mathbf{u}$}] at (U) {};
                        \node[point, label={[xshift=2pt,yshift=-2pt]right:$\mathbf{v}$}] at (V) {};
                        \node[bluepoint, label={[xshift=2pt,yshift=1pt]right:$\mathbf{w}$}] at (Wb) {};

                        \node[align=center] at (0,-3.2) {Linearly independent,\\ $\mathbf{w}$ does not lie in the plane determined by $\mathbf{u}$ and $\mathbf{v}$};
                    \end{scope}

                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
        </image>
    </figure>
    

    <example xml:id="ex-linearly-dependent-r2">
        <title>A Counterexample in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m></title>
        <p>
            Consider the vectors
            <me>\mathbf{v}_1 = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix}, \qquad \mathbf{v}_2 = \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix}.</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            Since <m>\mathbf{v}_2 = 2\mathbf{v}_1</m>, one vector is a scalar multiple of the other. Therefore, the vectors are not linearly independent. Indeed:
            <me>\mathbf{v}_2 = 2\mathbf{v}_1 \implies 2 \mathbf{v}_1 - \mathbf{v}_2 = \mathbf{0},</me>
            so we have found a non-trivial solution <m>x_1=2, x_2=-1</m> to the equation
            <me>x_1 \mathbf{v}_1 + x_2 \mathbf{x}_2 = \mathbf{0}.</me>
        </p>
    </example>

    <p>
        The most intuitive example of a basis is given by the standard coordinate axes.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="ex-basis">
        <title>Standard Basis in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m></title>
        <p>
            The vectors
            <me>\mathbf{e}_1 = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}, \qquad \mathbf{e}_2 = \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}</me>
            are linearly independent.
        </p>
        <p>
            Indeed, the equation
            <me>x_1 \mathbf{e}_1 + x_2 \mathbf{e}_2 = \mathbf{0}</me>
            becomes
            <me>\begin{pmatrix} x_1 \\ x_2 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix},</me>
            so necessarily <m>x_1 = 0</m> and <m>x_2 = 0</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            Hence, <m>(\mathbf{e}_1, \mathbf{e}_2)</m> is a basis of <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m>. This means that every vector in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> can be written uniquely as a linear combination of <m>\mathbf{e}_1</m> and <m>\mathbf{e}_2</m>.
        </p>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-linear-independence-r3">
        <title>Three Linearly Independent Vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m></title>
        <p>
            Consider the vectors
            <me>\mathbf{v}_1 = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}, \qquad \mathbf{v}_2 = \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}, \qquad \mathbf{v}_3 = \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}.</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            To test linear independence, we consider
            <me>x_1\mathbf{v}_1 + x_2\mathbf{v}_2 + x_3\mathbf{v}_3 = \mathbf{0}.</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            This gives
            <me>\begin{pmatrix} x_1 \\ x_2 \\ x_3 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix},</me>
            so <m>x_1 = x_2 = x_3 = 0</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            Therefore, the three vectors are linearly independent.
        </p>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-linear-dependence-r3">
        <title>A Counterexample with Three Vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m></title>
        <p>
            Consider the vectors
            <me>\mathbf{v}_1 = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}, \qquad \mathbf{v}_2 = \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}, \qquad \mathbf{v}_3 = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix}.</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            Since
            <me>\mathbf{v}_3 = \mathbf{v}_1 + \mathbf{v}_2,</me>
            the vector <m>\mathbf{v}_3</m> is a linear combination of the other two.
        </p>
        <p>
            Hence, the three vectors are not linearly independent.
        </p>
    </example>

    <p>
        Besides combining vectors algebraically, we also want to measure geometric quantities such as length, distance, and angle. These are based on the scalar product.
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-scalar-product-metrics">
        <title>Scalar Product, Norm, Distance, and Angle</title>
        <statement>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Scalar Product</title>
                    <p>
                        For vectors <m>\mathbf{v}, \mathbf{w} \in \mathbb{R}^n</m>, the scalar product is defined by
                        <me>\mathbf{v} \cdot \mathbf{w} = v_1 w_1 + \dots + v_n w_n.</me>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Norm</title>
                    <p>
                        The norm of <m>\mathbf{v}</m> is its length:
                        <me>\|\mathbf{v}\| = \sqrt{\mathbf{v} \cdot \mathbf{v}} = \sqrt{v_1^2 + \dots + v_n^2}.</me>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Distance</title>
                    <p>
                        The distance between <m>\mathbf{v}</m> and <m>\mathbf{w}</m> is
                        <me>\operatorname{dist}(\mathbf{v},\mathbf{w}) = \|\mathbf{v}-\mathbf{w}\| = \sqrt{(v_1-w_1)^2 + \dots + (v_n-w_n)^2}.</me>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Angle</title>
                    <p>
                        For two non-zero vectors <m>\mathbf{v}</m> and <m>\mathbf{w}</m>, the angle <m>\varphi</m> between them is defined by
                        <me>\varphi = \arccos\left(\frac{\mathbf{v} \cdot \mathbf{w}}{\|\mathbf{v}\| \|\mathbf{w}\|}\right).</me>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Orthogonality</title>
                    <p>
                        Two vectors <m>\mathbf{v}</m> and <m>\mathbf{w}</m> are called <term>orthogonal</term> if
                        <me>\mathbf{v} \cdot \mathbf{w} = 0.</me>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
        The formula for the norm is a direct generalization of the Pythagorean theorem. In two dimensions, a vector
        <m>\mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} v_1 \\ v_2 \end{pmatrix}</m>
        forms the hypotenuse of a right triangle whose legs have lengths <m>|v_1|</m> and <m>|v_2|</m>. Hence,
        <m>\|\mathbf{v}\| = \sqrt{v_1^2 + v_2^2}</m>.
        The same idea extends to higher dimensions.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="fig-norm-pythagoras">
        <title>Visualizing the Norm via the Pythagorean Theorem</title>
        <image xml:id="img-norm-pythagoras" width="65%">
            <description>A right-angled triangle formed by a vector and its components, with squares drawn on each side to geometrically illustrate that the square of the norm equals the sum of the squares of the components.</description>
            <latex-image>
                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
                    \draw[-&gt;, gray!50] (-4,0) -- (8,0) node[right] {$x$};
                    \draw[-&gt;, gray!50] (0,-4.5) -- (0,8) node[above] {$y$};

                    \draw[fill=blue!10, draw=blue, thick] (0,0) -- (4,0) -- (4,-4) -- (0,-4) -- cycle;
                    \node[blue, font=\large] at (2,-2) {Area $= v_1^2$};

                    \draw[fill=red!10, draw=red, thick] (4,0) -- (4,3) -- (7,3) -- (7,0) -- cycle;
                    \node[red, font=\large] at (5.5,1.5) {Area $= v_2^2$};

                    \draw[fill=gray!15, draw=black, thick] (0,0) -- (4,3) -- (1,7) -- (-3,4) -- cycle;
                    \node[black, font=\large, align=center] at (0.5,3.5) {Area $= \|\mathbf{v}\|^2$ \\ $= v_1^2 + v_2^2$};

                    \draw[thick] (3.6,0) -- (3.6,0.4) -- (4,0.4);

                    \draw[blue, ultra thick] (0,0) -- (4,0) node[midway, above, fill=white, inner sep=1pt] {$v_1$};
                    \draw[red, ultra thick] (4,0) -- (4,3) node[midway, left, fill=white, inner sep=1pt] {$v_2$};

                    \draw[-&gt;, black, ultra thick] (0,0) -- (4,3) node[midway, above left, inner sep=2pt] {$\|\mathbf{v}\| = \sqrt{v_1^2 + v_2^2}$};

                    \filldraw[black] (4,3) circle (2pt) node[anchor=south west] {$\mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} v_1 \\ v_2 \end{pmatrix}$};
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
        </image>
    </figure>

    <example xml:id="ex-scalar-product-norm">
        <title>Lengths and Orthogonality</title>
        <p>
            Consider the vectors
            <m>\mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix}</m>
            and
            <m>\mathbf{w} = \begin{pmatrix} -4 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix}</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            The norm of <m>\mathbf{v}</m> is
            <me>\|\mathbf{v}\| = \sqrt{3^2 + 4^2} = \sqrt{9 + 16} = \sqrt{25} = 5.</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            Their scalar product is
            <me>\mathbf{v} \cdot \mathbf{w} = (3)(-4) + (4)(3) = -12 + 12 = 0.</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            Since the scalar product is zero, the vectors are orthogonal.
        </p>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-engineering-state-vector">
        <title>A State Vector for Monitoring a Technical System</title>
        <p>
            In engineering applications, vectors are often used to represent system states rather than geometric arrows. For example, the operating condition of a motor might be described by the vector
            <me>\mathbf{x} = \begin{pmatrix} 1.8 \\ 0.3 \\ -0.5 \end{pmatrix},</me>
            where the components represent, for instance, a temperature deviation, a vibration level, and a current deviation.
        </p>
        <p>
            Another operating condition may be represented by
            <me>\mathbf{y} = \begin{pmatrix} 1.2 \\ 0.1 \\ -0.4 \end{pmatrix}.</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            The distance between the two states is
            <me>\operatorname{dist}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y}) = \|\mathbf{x}-\mathbf{y}\| = \sqrt{(1.8-1.2)^2 + (0.3-0.1)^2 + (-0.5-(-0.4))^2} = \sqrt{0.36 + 0.04 + 0.01} = \sqrt{0.41}.</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            This shows that vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> are not only geometric objects; they can also encode measurements and describe the state of a technical system.
        </p>
    </example>

    <exercises xml:id="exercises-vectors-reminder">
        <title>Check Your Understanding</title>

        <exercise xml:id="exer-mc-orthogonal">
            <title>Identifying Orthogonal Vectors</title>
            <statement>
                <p>Which of the following vectors is orthogonal to <m>\mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ -3 \end{pmatrix}</m>?</p>
            </statement>
            <choices>
                <choice>
                    <statement><p><m>\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix}</m></p></statement>
                    <feedback><p>Incorrect. The scalar product is <m>(2)(2) + (-3)(3) = 4 - 9 = -5</m>, not zero.</p></feedback>
                </choice>
                <choice correct="yes">
                    <statement><p><m>\begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix}</m></p></statement>
                    <feedback><p>Correct! The scalar product is <m>(2)(3) + (-3)(2) = 6 - 6 = 0</m>.</p></feedback>
                </choice>
                <choice>
                    <statement><p><m>\begin{pmatrix} -2 \\ -3 \end{pmatrix}</m></p></statement>
                    <feedback><p>Incorrect. The scalar product is <m>(2)(-2) + (-3)(-3) = -4 + 9 = 5</m>, not zero.</p></feedback>
                </choice>
                <choice>
                    <statement><p><m>\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}</m></p></statement>
                    <feedback><p>Incorrect. The scalar product is <m>(2)(1) + (-3)(1) = 2 - 3 = -1</m>, not zero.</p></feedback>
                </choice>
            </choices>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="exer-tf-basis">
            <title>Requirements for a Basis</title>
            <statement>
                <p>True or False: Any two non-zero vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> automatically form a basis of that space.</p>
            </statement>
            <choices>
                <choice>
                    <statement><p>True</p></statement>
                    <feedback><p>Incorrect. If the two vectors are scalar multiples of one another, then they are not linearly independent and therefore do not form a basis.</p></feedback>
                </choice>
                <choice correct="yes">
                    <statement><p>False</p></statement>
                    <feedback><p>Correct! Two vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> form a basis only if they are linearly independent.</p></feedback>
                </choice>
            </choices>
        </exercise>

    </exercises>
</subsection>